[[File:Adena burial in a simple log tomb.JPG|frame|right|An extended burial in a tomb of the Adena culture, North America.]] '''Shintensō''' (伸展葬, extended burial) refers to a burial method in [[cultural anthropology]] and [[archaeology]] where the body is placed in a fully extended position. This term primarily distinguishes it from {{ill|Flexed burial|ja|屈葬|lt=kusosō|12=draft}} (flexed burial). Variations include arms placed at the sides, hands positioned on the chest, or different orientations such as lying face-up (supine extended burial) or face-down (prone burial).
Among researchers, the distinction between shintensō and kusosō is not based solely on the posture of the body during burial. It is also defined by the presence of burial containers, such as coffins, or wrappings that explicitly support extended burial practices.
== References == * Mizuno Seiichi and Kobayashi Yukio, eds. *Illustrated Archaeological Dictionary*, Sōgensha, 1959.
